Targeting A Housing Subsidy

By Stephanie Onuaja

November 16, 2022

0.1 Motivation

The Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) in Emil City has a program that targets homeowners who qualify for a home repair tax credit. It has been around for 20 years with severely low rates of uptake from homeowners. They contact eligible homeowners each year, but not all eligible homeowners who enter the program take the credit. HCD allocates $2,850 in marketing per homeowner and the tax credit amounts to $5,000 per homeowner. Through program evaluation, researchers found that houses that transacted after taking the credit sold with a $10,000 premium. Additionally, homes surrounding the repaired home see an aggregate premium of $56,000, on average. To ensure homeowners in Emil City benefit from the home repair tax credit, I developed a decision-making tool to improve the outcome of homeowners receiving the tax credit. The goal is to convert the client-level data from previous campaigns into a decision-making analytic that would produce a more targeted campaign while reducing outreach costs.

0.2 Exploratory Analysis

0.2.1 Continuous Features

Starting with the continuous variables, the plots below group the continuous features by “yes” – meaning individuals that entered the program, and “no” – individuals that did not enter the program.


Housing %>%
  dplyr::select(y, unemploy_rate, age) %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y, value, fill=y)) + 
    geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat = "summary", fun = "mean") + 
    facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = palette2) +
    labs(x="TookCredit", y="Mean", 
         title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of enrollment in program",
         subtitle = "(Continous outcomes)") +
    plotTheme() + theme(legend.position = "none")

For age, it is a bit unclear how much more older homeowners tend to enroll in the program. On the other hand, more homeowners tend to enroll in the program when the unemployment rates were lower.

Housing %>%
  dplyr::select(y, inflation_rate, previous) %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y, value, fill=y)) + 
    geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat = "summary", fun = "mean") + 
    facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = palette2) +
    labs(x="TookCredit", y="Mean", 
         title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of enrollment in the program",
         subtitle = "(Continous outcomes)") +
    plotTheme() + theme(legend.position = "none")

Higher inflation rates decrease the likelihood of a homeowner enrolling in the program. The more times homeowners are contacted before a campaign increases the likelihood of them enrolling in the program.

0.2.2 Two category features (Yes/No)

Housing %>%
  dplyr::select(y, mortgage, taxbill_in_phl) %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
  count(Variable, value, y) %>%
  filter(value == "yes") %>%
    ggplot(aes(y, n, fill = y)) +   
      geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat="identity") +
      facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free", ncol=4) +
      scale_fill_manual(values = palette2) +
      labs(x="TookCredit", y="Count",
           title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of enrollment in program",
           subtitle = "Two category features (Yes and No)") +
      plotTheme() + theme(legend.position = "none")

More people that do not enroll in the program are owners with mortgages and full-time residents in Philadelphia. This shows that most homeowners do not enroll in this program.

0.2.3 Multiple category features

Housing %>% 
  dplyr::select(y, poutcome, marital, job, education, contact, month) %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
  count(Variable, value, y) %>%
  ggplot(aes(value, n, fill = y)) +   
    geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat="identity") +
    facet_wrap(~Variable, scales="free") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = palette2) +
    labs(x="TookCredit", y="Count",
         title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of taking tax credit",
         subtitle = "Multiple category features") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))

The plots suggest that the most effective means of contact is through cellular. University degree holders are the most likely to enroll in the program. Married households are most likely to enroll in the program, and at the same time, they are the most likely not to enroll in the program compared to the other households. Where outcomes of the previous marketing campaign were non-existent, the likelihood of people not enrolling in the program was the highest.

0.3 Logistic Regression

0.3.1 Training / Test sets

The data was spit into a 65/35 training set/ test set.

set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(Housing$y, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
yTrain <- Housing[ trainIndex,]
yTest  <- Housing[-trainIndex,]

0.3.2 Regression 1 - Kitchen sink model

Without engineering any features in the dataset, I ran the regression with the features as is. The kitchen sink model had a McFadden of 0.1943092.

0.3.3 Feature Engineering

To optimize the features in the Housing dataset and prevent collinearity in features with multiple categories, I created new features with clearer categories which would be part of the logistic regression. The newly engineered features regrouped education into 4 groups, age into 3 age groups, jobs into 3 employment categories, and months into seasons.

# Education
Housing$edugroups <- sapply(Housing$education, switch, 
                  basic.4y = 'lessthanHS', 
                  basic.6y = 'lessthanHS', 
                  basic.9y = 'lessthanHS', 
                  high.school = 'HS', 
                  illiterate = 'other', 
                  university.degree = 'Higheredu', 
                  professional.course = 'Higheredu',
                  unknown = 'other')

# Age Groups, 35 and below = Young adults, 35 to 65 = Middle-aged, above 65 = Old-aged 
Housing <- 
  mutate(Housing, agegroups = case_when(age <= 35 ~ "Young adults", 
                                        age >=36 & age <= 65 ~ "Middle-aged",
                                        age >= 66 ~ "Old-aged"))

# Employment status
  Housing <- 
  mutate(Housing, Employ = case_when(job == "student" | job == "unemployed" | job == "retired" ~ "unemployed",
                                   TRUE  ~ "employed"))        

# Season
Housing <-
  Housing %>%
  mutate(Season = case_when(
    month == "dec" |month == "jan" | month == "feb" ~ "Winter",
    month == "mar" |month == "apr" | month == "may" ~ "Spring",
    month == "jun" |month == "jul" | month == "aug" ~ "Summer",
    month == "sep" |month == "oct" | month == "nov" ~ "Fall"))

0.3.4 Regression 2 - Engineered model

With the engineered features I ran a second regression and tested for the goodness of fit. The McFadden score of the engineered model was lower than the kitchen sink model, at 0.1703072. While the McFadden score of the engineered model was lower, it does not vary greatly from the kitchen sink model. Multiple variations of engineered features were tested, and the scores remained slightly below 0.19. Hence, the model will be used to further this analysis.


set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(Housing$y, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
yTrain <- Housing[ trainIndex,]
yTest  <- Housing[-trainIndex,]

Using an alternative approach to the goodness of fit, I predicted the rate that “yes” and “no” are predicted correctly.

testProbs <- data.frame(Outcome = as.factor(yTest$y_numeric),
                        Probs = predict(reg2, yTest, type= "response"))
head(testProbs)

       title = "Distribution of predicted probabilities by observed outcome") +
  plotTheme() + theme(strip.text.x = element_text(size = 18),
        legend.position = "none")

The model does better at predicting “no” - homeowners that did not receive the credit vs. “yes” - the ones that took the credit.

0.4 Goodness of Fit

0.4.1 Confusion Matrix

The Confusion Matrix shows the number of observed instances of homeowners taking the credit, which is predicted as such. Each entry in the matrix provides a different comparison between observed and predicted, given the 50% threshold.

There were 36 true positives (when “yes” was correctly predicted as a “yes”). There were 121 false positives (when “yes” was incorrectly predicted as a “no”) There were 1264 true negatives (when “no was correctly predicted as a”no) there were 19 false negatives ( when “no” was incorrectly predicted as “yes”)

testProbs <- 
  testProbs %>%
  mutate(predOutcome  = as.factor(ifelse(testProbs$Probs > 0.5 , 1, 0)))

0.4.3 Cross Validation

Using the cross-validation tool, I derived the ROC, Sensitivity, and Specificity for both models. The trainControl ran 100 k-folds, outputting predicted probabilities for “yes” and “no”. The kitchen sink and engineered models produced similar outputs for the ROC, sensitivity, and specificity. The models are generalizable if the distribution is tighter to the mean. Both models are not as generalizable in terms of specificity - the rate it correctly predicts true negatives (did not take tax credit). However, both models perfectly predict true positives (Sensitivity).

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100, classProbs=TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)

0.5 Cost/Benefit Analysis

The cost/benefit analysis was developed with the following parameters:

  • Marketing Costs: $2,850

  • Credit allocated per household: $5,000.

  • 25% of eligible homeowners receive credit

Below the cost/benefit for each outcome in our confusion matrix is calculated:

  • True Negative: Predicted correctly homeowner would not take the credit, no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated. $0

  • True Positive: Predicted correctly homeowner would enter the credit program; allocated the marketing resources, and 25% ultimately achieved the credit. Marketing Resources were allocated to 100%, although only 25% receive the credit. $-2850 for 75% of the homeowners that did not receive the credit and $-7850 for the 25% that receive the credit.

  • False Negative: Predicted that a homeowner would not take the credit but they did. $0

  • False Positive: Predicted incorrectly homeowner would take the credit; allocated marketing resources; no credit allocated. $-2850

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
               case_when(Variable == "True_Negative"  ~ Count * 0,
                         Variable == "True_Positive"  ~ (Count * -2850) - ((Count * .25) * -5000),
                         Variable == "False_Negative" ~ (0) * Count,
                         Variable == "False_Positive" ~ (- 2850) * Count)) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "Predicted HO would not take the credit, no marketing, and no credit was allocated",
              "Predicted HO would enter credit program and allocated the marketing resources, and 25% took the credit",
              "Predicted HO would not take the credit but they did",
              "Predicted that HO would take the credit, allocated marketing resources, no credit allocated")))

kable(cost_benefit_table,
       caption = "Cost/Benefit Table") %>% kable_styling()

Regarding this program, the revenue of $0 is positive because the departments spend less on outreach and saves money. However, only 25% of the homeowners ultimately receive the credit, and the department loses a lot of money from the marketing efforts allotted to the other 75% of eligible homeowners (true positive). False positives also cost the department a lot of money.

  whichThreshold %>%
    dplyr::select(starts_with("Count"), Threshold) %>%
    gather(Variable, Count, -Threshold) %>%
    mutate(Revenue =
             case_when(Variable == "Count_TN"  ~  Count * 0,
                       Variable == "Count_TP"  ~ (Count * -2850) - ((Count * .25) * -5000),
                       Variable == "Count_FN"  ~ (0) * Count,
                       Variable == "Count_FP"  ~  (- 2850) * Count))

       y = "Revenue") +
  plotTheme() +
  guides(colour=guide_legend(title = "Confusion Matrix"))

The revenue starts to flatten out to $0 at a threshold of 0.5. To minimize costs, the threshold should be set between 0.5 to 1.


whichThreshold_revenue <- 
  whichThreshold %>% 
    mutate(tookCredit = ifelse(Variable == "Count_TP", (Count * .5),
                         ifelse(Variable == "Count_FN", Count, 0))) %>% 
    group_by(Threshold) %>% 
    summarize(Total_Revenue = sum(Revenue),
              Total_Count_of_Credit = sum(tookCredit))

0.6 Conclusion

I would recommend this model into production, however, there is still room for improvement. The model is excellent at predicting true positives, but, the financial loss in this category is attributed to the fact that only 25% ultimately achieved the credit. The model is not good at predicting false positives, which means a sizable portion of the marketing resources goes to waste.

In this analysis, adding engineered features to the dataset did not necessarily yield better results than expected. Further analysis of the data should be carried out to engineer better features that may significantly impact the model. Using the optimal threshold of 95% ensures that the least amount of money is spent or “wasted”. However, since the goal is to increase the number of homeowners who would benefit from this program, it is further measures need to be taken to improve the response rate.

The marketing campaign needs to adjust according to the patterns identified in the data. For example, cell phones were the most effective form of contact for marketing initiatives. Married households were most likely to enroll in the program and the summer months had the highest amounts of enrollment in the tax credit.
